Parsing the Data¶

In [3]:
def read_csv(data_dir, data):
    
    assert data.endswith('csv'), "File has to be in .csv"
    
    file_path = data_dir + data
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
    df.drop('Unnamed: 0', axis=1, inplace=True)
    df.vin = data[:5] #assuring the correct vin name 
    df.timestamp_utc = pd.to_datetime(df.timestamp_utc)
    df['year'] = df.timestamp_utc.dt.year
    df['month'] = df.timestamp_utc.dt.month
    df['day'] = df.timestamp_utc.dt.day
    df['doy'] = df.timestamp_utc.dt.dayofyear
    df['time_spent']=df.timestamp_utc.diff().shift(-1)
    df['maxima'] = df.sig_value[(df.sig_value > df.sig_value.shift(1)) & (df.sig_value > df.sig_value.shift(-1))]
    df['minima'] = df.sig_value[(df.sig_value < df.sig_value.shift(1)) & (df.sig_value < df.sig_value.shift(-1))]
    return df
In [4]:
def read_csvs(data_dir):
    data_dict={}   
    for data in os.listdir(data_dir):
        if data.endswith('csv'):
            df = read_csv(data_dir, data)
            data_dict[data[:5]] = df
    return data_dict

Every vehicle (except car_3 and car_7) will have -1024.0 as sig_value if sig_text is SNA, and the converse is true. Confirmed by Han: SNA means signal not available, for IoT devices, its essentially an error in data collection. Its a default value when something went wrong with the measurement. For the purposes of this, feel free to ignore SNA data.

def plot_by_day(car_num, sig_text=True):
    test = data_dict[car_num].copy()
    if not sig_text:
        test = test[test.sig_value != -1024.0]
    test_gp = test.groupby('day')
    groups = test_gp.groups.keys()
    print "Available Days:{}".format(groups)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows = len(test_gp.groups.keys()), ncols= 1,figsize = (20,100))
    for i, day in enumerate(groups): 
        ax = axes.flat[i]
        plot_df = test_gp.get_group(day)
        ax.plot(plot_df.timestamp_utc, plot_df.sig_value, 'o', color=tesla_red, lw=0.1, alpha=0.5)
        ax.set_title(day)
    if car_num == "car_3" or car_num == "car_7":
        ax.set_ylim(-300,460)
    else:
        ax.set_ylim(-450, 1320)

def drop_consecutive_values(df):
    i = 0
    shape_old = df.shape[0]
    shape_new = 0
    while shape_old != shape_new:
        df_shift = df.loc[df.sig_value.shift()!=df.sig_value]
        shape_new = df_shift.shape[0]
        df = df_shift
        i += 1 
#         print "{}th iteration: diff is {}".format(i, np.abs(shape_new-shape_old))
        shape_old = shape_new
#     print "After {}th iteration, dropped all the consecutive duplicates".format(i)
    df = df[(~df.maxima.isnull()) | (~df.minima.isnull())].reset_index(drop=True)
    return df

def get_cycle_info(df):
    df['minima'] = df.minima.shift()
    df = df.dropna(axis=0, subset=['maxima', 'minima']).reset_index(drop=True)
    df['amplitude'] = np.abs(df.maxima.values - df.minima.values)
    df['cycle_length'] = df.timestamp_utc.diff().shift(-1).dt.total_seconds()
    return df 

def get_largest_cycle(df, n=1, top=True):
    df = drop_consecutive_values(df)
    df = get_cycle_info(df)
    df = df.sort_values('amplitude', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)
    if top:
        return df.iloc[:n][['maxima', 'minima','amplitude','cycle_length']]
    else: 
        return df.iloc[-n:][['maxima', 'minima','amplitude','cycle_length']]

Comparing Distributions¶

In [17]:
def compare_metrics():
    metric_collection = {}
    for car, test in data_dict.iteritems():
        metric_collection[car] = {}
        test_temp = test[test.shift().sig_value != test.sig_value]
        test_index = test_temp.index[test_temp.sig_value == -1024.0]
        
        test_list = []
        for k, idx in enumerate(test_index):
            if k+1 < len(test_index):
                df = test_temp.loc[idx:test_index[k+1]]
                test_list.append(df)
            
        test_min = []
        test_max = []
        test_mean = []
        test_var = []

        for k, df in enumerate(test_list):
            df = df[df.sig_value != -1024.0]
            test_min.append(df.sig_value.min())
            test_max.append(df.sig_value.max())
            test_mean.append(df.sig_value.mean())
            test_var.append(df.sig_value.std())
        
        metric_collection[car]['min']=test_min
        metric_collection[car]['max']=test_max
        metric_collection[car]['mean']=test_mean
        metric_collection[car]['var']=test_var
        
    return metric_collection

▪︎ Number of Occurence¶

In [22]:
def get_by_total_occurrence(df, n=1, top=True, start_date=None, end_date=None):
        """
        Get the top N most/least common values by total occurence.

        Args:
            df         (DataFrame): DataFrame that contains full timeseries.
            n          (int): Number of results the user wants to see.
            top        (boolean): If wants to see top results, set to True,
                                if least set to False.
            start_date (str): Start date of the search range. "YYYY-MM-DD"
            end_date   (str): End date of the search range. "YYYY-MM-DD"

        Returns:
            List of top n most/least common values by total occurence.

        """
        df_time = df.set_index('timestamp_utc')
        if start_date:
            df_time = df_time.loc[start_date:]
        if end_date:
            df_time = df_time.loc[:end_date]
        val_count = Counter(df_time.sig_value)
        if top:
            return val_count.most_common()[:n]
        else:
            return val_count.most_common()[-n:]

▪︎ Total number of time spent¶

In [24]:
def get_by_total_time_spent(df, n=1, top=True, start_date=None, end_date=None):
    """
    Get the top N most/least common values by total time spent.

    Args:
        df         (DataFrame): DataFrame that contains full timeseries.
        n          (int): Number of results the user wants to see.
        top        (boolean): If wants to see top results, set to True,
                              if least set to False.
        start_date (str): Start date of the search range. "YYYY-MM-DD"
        end_date   (str): End date of the search range. "YYYY-MM-DD"

    Returns:a
        List of top n most/least common values by total time spent.

    """
    df_time = df.set_index('timestamp_utc')
    if start_date:
        df_time = df_time.loc[start_date:]
    if end_date:
        df_time = df_time.loc[:end_date] # remember the days could be different  . .     
    df_time = df_time.groupby('sig_value').agg({'time_spent': 'sum'})
    df_time = df_time.sort_values('time_spent', ascending=False)
    if top:
        return df_time.iloc[:n]
    else:
        return df_time.iloc[-n:]

One thing we have to remember is that the signal data is not always collected. In other words, there could be a gap between two data points, not because the torque sensor remained at the same value, but merely because the vehicle was not running. We need a better way to distinguish such a case.

In [26]:
def get_by_total_time_spent_2(df, n=1, top=True):
    df_pivot = pd.pivot_table(df, index='day', columns='sig_value',
                              values='time_spent', aggfunc=np.sum,
                              fill_value=0, margins=True,
                              margins_name='Total Time Spent')
    df_unstack = df_pivot.unstack().xs(
        'Total Time Spent', level='day')[:-1]
    df_res = pd.DataFrame(df_unstack).reset_index().rename(
        columns={0: 'total_time_spent'})
    df_res = df_res.sort_values(
        'total_time_spent', ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True).reset_index(drop=True)

    if top:
        return df_res.iloc[:n]
    else:
        return df_res.iloc[-n:]
